🚀 Creating & Connecting to Amazon EC2 (Linux & Windows)
🌐 1️⃣ Create & Connect to Linux EC2 (Ubuntu)
🔹 Launch Ubuntu EC2 Instance in Amazon Web Services
4
Steps:
Go to AWS Console → EC2 → Launch Instance
Choose Ubuntu Server AMI
Select instance type (e.g., t2.micro – Free Tier)
Create/Select Key Pair (.pem)
Configure Security Group:
Type: SSH
Port: 22
Source: My IP
Launch Instance

🔐 Connect to Ubuntu EC2 Using PuTTY (.ppk)
✅ Prerequisites
Ubuntu EC2 running
Public IP / DNS
PuTTY installed (Windows)
.ppk key file
Download PuTTY:
https://www.putty.org
🔹 Step 1: Convert .pem to .ppk (If Needed)
4
Open PuTTYgen
Click Load
Select .pem file (choose All Files)
Click Save private key
Save as .ppk
✔ Conversion complete
🔹 Step 2: Configure PuTTY
4
Open PuTTY
In Session:
Host Name:
ubuntu@<Public-IP>
Go to:
Connection → SSH → Auth → Credentials
Browse & select .ppk file
Click Open
Click Yes (Security Alert)
🎉 Connected!
🧪 Verify:
whoami
Output:
ubuntu

☁️ Connect Using AWS CloudShell
4
Open CloudShell (top-right terminal icon)
Go to EC2 → Instance → Connect
Choose SSH Client
Copy the ssh -i command
Upload .pem file into CloudShell
Run:
chmod 400 keyname.pem
ssh -i keyname.pem ubuntu@<public-ip>
✅ Connected Successfully

🖥️ Create & Connect Windows EC2 (RDP)
🔹 Step 1: Launch Windows Instance
4
EC2 → Launch Instance
Choose Windows Server 2019/2022
Choose instance type
Security Group:
Type: RDP
Port: 3389
Source: My IP
Download Key Pair (.pem)
Launch
🔹 Step 2: Get Administrator Password
4
Select Instance → Connect
Choose RDP Client
Click Get Password
Upload .pem
Click Decrypt
Copy Password
🔹 Step 3: Connect via RDP
Press Windows + R
Type:
mstsc
Enter Public IP/DNS
Username: Administrator
Paste password
🎉 Windows Desktop appears

🌍 Install & Deploy NGINX on Ubuntu EC2
🔹 Install Nginx
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx -y
